post_text:
Jefferson Joint School District 251 is excited to announce the Food Service Program will be providing free breakfast and lunch meals to all students enrolled in the school district.

The meals will come as an extension of the U.S. Department of Agriculture's National School Lunch Program, which was enacted to assist families still being affected by the novel coronavirus. The coverage for free meals will last through the end of the year (December 31, 2020), or until federal funding runs out.

For all families that have not already submitted a Free/Reduced Meal Application, we encourage you to fill one out online at: https://jeffersonsd251.org/our-district/school-lunch/ . Applications processed assist the district with Title 1 funding and grants the district receives to assist students.

If you have any questions call the Child Nutrition Office at (208) 745-6693 Ext. 1138 or e-mail: dtimm@sd251.org.

We look forward to welcoming our students back to school on Wednesday, September 2. Our goal is to provide a safe learning environment for students for the entire school year. We are asking families to partner with us in this goal by following local health department guidance, including monitoring health symptoms, keeping students’ home when they are sick and wearing face coverings when physical distancing is not possible. We also encourage students to bring their own water bottles and personal hand sanitizer with them to school.

If you have any questions on your students bus route call the Transportation Department at (208) 754-8211 or refer to the Ride 360 App https://jeffersonsd251.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/traversa3.pdf.

Together we are going to make this a great school year!

Sincerely,

Superintendent-Chad Martin

post_text:
Back to School

Jefferson School District’s Plan is to resume in-school face-to-face instruction, on Wednesday, September 2, unless otherwise directed by the State Board of Education or the local health department. For families who are not comfortable returning to school, Jefferson School District will offer an online option through Rigby Virtual Academy.

Planning for the Future

We cannot predict the course of the current worldwide pandemic. We are hoping that the spread will have slowed – or ended.

One of the lessons we have learned from this spring is that Jefferson School District 251 needs to be prepared for any scenario. In preparation for the 2020-2021 school year, school staff and district leaders have prepared three scenarios for returning. Additionally, there will be an option for families who choose not to send their students to school because of concerns about COVID-19.

Please visit our district website at https://jeffersonsd251.org/ for more back to school information.

post_text:
Dear Parents/Guardians,

The Jefferson School District Board of Trustees has determined to continue with distance learning until the end of the school year (June 4), because of the COVID-19 pandemic.

That soft closure began in the Jefferson School District on Wednesday, March 15, and since that time, our educators and staff have worked hard to provide students the best possible remote learning and digital instruction we can offer. We recognize the challenge this has placed on you and your children and we will continue to do our best to help students prosper.

There are certainly many logistical matters to take care of before the end of the school year and we will get specific information to you, through your building principal, as soon as possible regarding end-of-year procedures, including graduation.

These are incredibly unstable and trying times, and we thank you for your ongoing efforts to help us provide an education for your children.

Warmest regards,

Chad Martin
Superintendent

This Friday night, April 10th, 2020, we are lighting up our stadium at Rigby High School to participate in the "Be The Light” campaign.
As a symbol of hope and support to all of our students, our stadium lights at Rigby High School will be shinning bright from 8:00 pm to 8:20 pm.
We want our students to know that we miss you, that we are thinking of you, and that we will get through this challenging time.
We especially want our Senior class to know that our hearts and minds are with each of you. The 20 minute time frame is for the Class of 2020.
Those that decide to drive by, please stay in your vehicle. The facilities and parking lots will be closed.
If you wish to share your pictures or experience, please use #BeTheLightID.

post_text:
Dear Parents,

The Board of Trustees met tonight and approved the districts recommendation to institute a “soft close” tomorrow Tuesday, March 17th. We highly recommend that parents keep students home. However, we will be open for those students who have no other childcare options. Buses will run their scheduled routes tomorrow for those students who need to attend school tomorrow, Tuesday, March 17th. Additionally, schools will be open for students to come and get their belongings during regular hours on Tuesday only.

Beginning Wednesday, March 18th, schools will be closed for spring break extending until Friday April 3rd. As the situation evolves in regards to COVID-19 we will provide further information.

Thank you for your input, patience and understanding as we continue to respond to the most recent information and recommendations from government and health officials.

Sincerely,
Superintendent- Chad Martin

post_text:
Today is "School Bus Driver Appreciation Day!" We want to show our appreciation and thank our transportation staff for all they do to assure our students are transported safely each day of the school year.

Here a few Jefferson School District 251 transportation facts:
*Jefferson School District employs 63 bus drivers and 6 bus aides.
*Those bus drivers transport an average of 3,207 students daily.
*Our bus drivers travel over 604,760 miles in a school year.

post_text:
The Jefferson School District 251 will present SCREENAGERS: Growing Up in the Digital Age. This is a documentary about the biggest parenting issue of our time. SCREENAGERS reveals how tech time impacts development and offers solutions on how adults can empower their kids to best navigate the digital world to find balance.

Please join us on September 23 at 6:30 p.m., in the Rigby High School Auditorium for this special event for families.

post_text:
We are exciting for the work that has been done over the summer on our construction projects. Work will continue through the winter. While construction continues throughout the school year, both Harwood and Midway will be ready for students on September 4. We are working closely with contractors to ensure the safety of our students and minimizing distractions to learning. We anticipate all three projects to be completed for the 2020-2021 school year.

We want to thank our parents, teachers and staff for their patience and support as these much needed improvements are made to our schools.
